task.summary: Default task
Using box2d for the game world
Using box2d for the game world
Player renders with the correct position and size;
Map file parser is implemented.
Obstacle tiles added. Player uses a circle for bounds, to avoid rectangle snags. Radius of said circle is reduced to account for map blocks.
Resizes properly.
Borders on obstacle tiles.
Lots of changes. Now is 3d. Box2d is out, bullet is in. Tiles are solid objects, and the player tile rests on the base tiles.
Player tile moves with user input. Camera follows player.
Bullet is out. Simulating physics. Core was split into a model-view-controller layout.
GPL licensed added to the source.
Rough and Goal tiles functional.
Camera does it's job. Needs more work doe.
Movement now takes advantage of Vector3.lerp. Very smooth, no more jumpy jitters.
Rendering code changed to allow generation of level meshes.
60 fps, everything works.
per-face culling introduced.
TileMazeParser stores end position now. GameControlsMenu is functional again.
main menu and level select screen
main menu and level select screen
level changed to levels
level manager added
Progress database and service implemented.
Level and floor select in progress.
Level and floor select in progress.
Test levels introduced. Will be made awesome at a later date.
Floor selector visible.
Floor selector functional... and gross. But progress has been made. Decades from now, children will remember this day and look back in awe of their forefathers accomplishments.
More test floors.
Loads and displays all the floors for each level.
Levels render aligned properly.
Reorganized code base.
Reorganized code base.
Player can navigate between levels. Saves level progress. Unvisited levels are now locked.
Custom camera controller introduced. Player following and camera movement is works nicely. Objects can also now listen to changes in player position.
Camera can now be rotated properly, and is limited correctly.
Movement orients to the camera's x angle.
Uses shader fonts and shader labels. Needs shader buttons tho.
Moved call to level database service in level select screen to once in the constructor. Loads much faster now.
floor 1-4 is a reproduction of a pokemon ice maze. It's really hard and fun!
Fixed bug where all the levels had the same number of floors (11).
Improved camera zoom. Translates instead of zooms, as it is more appropriate.
Improved camera zoom. Translates instead of zooms, as it is more appropriate.
Improved camera zoom. Translates instead of zooms, as it is more appropriate.

MASSIVE changes to the core in preparation of a level/floor editor. Floor introduced in order to seperate the floor data from TileMaze. TileMaze changed to TileMazeSimulator, and now uses Floor (and TileSectors) to resolve movements.
Player changed to PlayerTransformer and a lot of other stuff refactored so PlayerRender and PlayerTransformer are seperated.
Level service added for reading/writing levels to json. Files licenses updated.
Imports optimized.

Level files are stored as json now! ".dat" files are thrown out, because base64 encoding increases the size by 1/3. Finally, uses google's Gson library for parsing json files, as libgdx's json utilities can't handle generics very well.
TilePallete fully integrated. TileData no longer stores color data.
Tile data is now deprecated. Tile type is kept in tilestack. The tilestack is now just a holder for whatever array it needs to hold. Uses less space in the level json :)
MasterSector object is now in. Has issues with generating new sub sectors though.
MasterSector seems to build correctly, and has the right structure. Gson causes android to run out of memory now though. The nightmare bugs from hell continue! Stay tuned for the next episode!
